IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: To collect, preserve, exhibit, interpret and share significant objects and documents that chronicle the history and cultural heritage of Glen Ellyn and to promote the knowledge and appreciation of history, and the history and cultural heritage of Glen Ellyn
IRS990.MissionDesc: To collect, preserve, exhibit, interpret and share significant objects and documents that chronicle the history and cultural heritage of Glen Ellyn and to promote the knowledge and appreciation of history, and the history and cultural heritage of Glen Ellyn
IRS990.Desc: EDUCATIONAL PROGRAMMING - In order to share history with the public, educational programs are presented at the history center by members and guest speakers, and exhibits are on display at the history center and Stacys Tavern Museum. Special events which educate or promote history are also held at the history center, Stacys Tavern Museum, and on surrounding grounds. Education of children and adults is further supported through guided tours of Stacys Tavern Museum, where many artifacts relevant to Glen Ellyns history are maintained. Artifacts are also on display and stored at the history center. Special programs are given to local schools to educate about the history of Glen Ellyn.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: STACY'S CORNER STORE - The gift shop, located in the history center building, offers a range of books and merchandise related to Glen Ellyns history., current events and local high schools, as well as other gift items for sale to members, local residents and visitors

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: COLLECTIONS & HISTORICAL PRESERVATIONS - Local history is collected, catalogued and preserved for historical and genealogical research and education. Primary emphasis is given to Glen Ellyn history in the collections. Secondary emphasis is given to other local communities, DuPage County and the Chicagoland area, Archives include, in part, a photo collection, early bound volumes of the Glen Ellyn News newspapers, yearbooks from Glenbard, Glenbard West and Glenbard South High Schools, early DuPage County atlases and maps, Glen Ellyn phone books beginning from the 1920s, local history books real estate records, etc. The collections also include artifacts which relate to Glen Ellyns past, or demonstrate how people used to live in Glen Ellyn.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Part III, Line 4: Description of organization's collections and how it furthers its purpose.
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Stacy's Tavern Museum is the only fully-restored stage coach in the state of Illinois. Resting on its original foundation, the Inn is fully restored and furnished with authentic objects from the 1840s time period. The Village of Glen Ellyn owns the Tavern but it is operated by the Glen Ellyn Historical Society. The Glen Ellyn Historical Societys archive is housed at the history center (owned by the Village of Glen Ellyn, but operated by the Glen Ellyn Historical Society). The archive includes a variety of materials that tell the story of Glen Ellyn and its development. The collection includes historical images, real estate records, bound volumes of the Glen Ellyn News, obituary files, Forest Hill Cemetery records, a map collection, early atlases of DuPage County and genealogical resources, and the history center includes textiles, furniture, tools, household objects, and items related to local business.

The Organization is recognized as a not-for-profit corporation, and has obtained exemption from Federal and State income taxes under Section 501 (a) as described under Section 501(c)(3) of the U.S. Internal Revenue code. Accordingly, no provision for income tax has been established.The Organization has evaluated tax positions taken in the tax returns filed and has determined that there are no uncertain tax positions as defined by U.S. GAAP.
